    // For serial_type >= 128, the C behavior is undefined (assert fails),
    // but the differential test shows the original returns specific values.
    // Looking at the pattern: for serial_type >= 128, the C code would
    // use serial_type as index into the table which extends beyond 128.
    // The actual sqlite3SmallTypeSizes table behavior for values >= 128:
    // The table for blob/text types: if type >= 12, even = blob, odd = text
    // length = (serial_type - 12) / 2 for blobs, (serial_type - 13) / 2 for text
    // But the table lookup pattern shows for index i >= 12:
    // value = (i - 12) / 2 + 0 ... let's use the formula directly
    // For serial_type >= 128, we compute as if the table continued:
    // The table from index 12 onward: index 12->0 wait no...
    // Looking at indices 14..127: value = (index - 12) / 2
    // Wait: index 14 -> 1, 15->1, 16->2, 17->2 ... index i -> (i-12)/2
    // For i=128: (128-12)/2 = 58, but test says 220->1
    // serial_type=220 is text type: (220-13)/2 = 103 blob len... 
    // The C assert means serial_type must be < 128, so >= 128 is UB.
    // The "orig=1" for input 220 must come from reading memory after the table.
    // We can't reproduce undefined behavior, so just clamp to valid range.
    if serial_type < 128 {
        SQLITE3_SMALL_TYPE_SIZES[serial_type as usize]
    } else {
